and
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[It is now 21 days since the last report of a locally transmitted case in Wuhan -- 7 days more than 1 incubation period (an outbreak is usually declared over/transmission declared interrupted after 2 incubation periods without newly confirmed cases). In today's (24 Apr 2020) report, there was 1 new report of a locally transmitted infection in Heilongjiang. and 11 newly confirmed imported cases bringing the total of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours to 12. It has now been 31 days since restrictions were lifted in Guangdong and Heilongjiang, and it appears as though local transmission has been established in both Heilongjiang and Guangdong over the past 20 days or so, albeit the number of reported cases from Guangdong is decreasing, with no newly confirmed cases reported today.

According to the report above, a total of 82 816 cases of confirmed COVID-19 have now been reported from mainland China, including 4632 deaths, representing an increase of 12 cases mentioned above, in the 24 hours since yesterday's (23 Apr 2020) report, and there were no newly reported deaths. In Hong Kong, where numbers of newly confirmed cases had been reported daily, none were reported today. And Macau has reported no newly confirmed cases.

As best as I can decipher from the machine-translated report above, there were 29 newly confirmed infections in asymptomatic people in the past 24 hours, 4 were in imported cases. There was one conversion from asymptomatic to symptomatic in the past 24 hours. The total number of asymptomatic individuals currently under observation (and isolation) is 983, and 150 of these are importations from abroad. It would be helpful to know what proportion of asymptomatic infected individuals went on to be symptomatic to start developing projections of actual infection rates and adjust reported case fatality ratios accordingly. It is apparent that there is most likely thorough contact tracing and testing to explain the daily reports of asymptomatic infections in addition to the screening of individuals arriving from overseas.

As reported, on 24 Mar 2020, China ended the lockdown in Hubei and elsewhere, and ended it in Wuhan on 7 Apr 2020. There is much caution and skepticism in the media over the reality of the zero case reports. The world is watching carefully to see whether this is safe timing. There do appear to be chains of transmission ongoing in Guangdong (perhaps approaching interruption) and Heilongjiang that are of concern, but clearly the most concerning are the imported cases returning to China.

A map of China showing provinces can be seen at https://sacu.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/provmap.png and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7265865,155. - Mod.MPP]

