[The tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Italy is now 192 994 cases, including 25 969 deaths, up from 189 973 cases and 25 549 deaths reported on 23 Apr 2020. The 24-hour change between 23 and 24 Apr 2020 was 3021 newly confirmed cases, compared with 2646 newly confirmed cases between 22 Apr 2020 and 23 Apr 2020 -- a slow vacillating but steady decline. Numbers of hospitalized cases and numbers of cases in the ICU are also experiencing a decline. Cases continue to be concentrated in the northern part of the country, in Lombardy, the epicenter of the outbreak, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto, and Piedmont. These 4 provinces combined account for 78.4% of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours. Lombardy is the main contributor representing 36.1% of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours. Liguria is the only other province reporting more than 100 cases in the past 24 hours (4.1% of newly reported cases). 5 provinces reported less than 10 newly confirmed cases and another 7 provinces reported less than 50 newly confirmed cases. All signs of decreasing local transmission. There is an excellent interactive map at http://opendatadpc.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/b0c68bce2cce478eaac82fe38d4138b1 to visualize the caseloads per region in near real time.

On 9 Mar 2020, Italy announced a lockdown for the northern provinces where the outbreak was concentrated. On 10 Mar 2020, this was expanded to be countrywide. On 11 Mar 2020, Italy announced the closure of non-essential businesses. It is now 38 days since the start of the lockdown in the north and 36 days since the countrywide lockdown. The lockdown is being extended until 3 May 2020 (see ProMED-mail post 20200411.7211958 for details).

A map of Italy showing regions can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/italy/regions.html and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7265865,75. - Mod.MPP]

